League of Legends High Elo Ranked Games - Exploratory Data Analysis¶

by Libertad Rodriguez¶

Introduction¶

League of Legends is a popular moba game allowing people to partake in ranked games against other players where their performance is measured and the better you are (the more you win) the higher you can climb the ranked ladder. High Elo consists of the top 3 ranks in the game; Master, Grand Master, and Challenger. Less than 1% of the entire player base reach these ranks (https://www.esportstales.com/league-of-legends/rank-distribution-percentage-of-players-by-tier). During the game you either play as part of the red side or the blue side. The side you're on affects your in-game view.

This dataset consists of three CSV files each formatted identically. Each file represents one High Elo rank. There is one file for Master games, one for Grand Master games, and one for Challenger games.

The Master_Ranked_Games file consists of 107125 rows and 50 columns. The GrandMaster_Ranked_Games file consists of 65896 rows and 50 columns. The Challenger_Ranked_Games file consists of 26904 rows and 50 columns.

Each row containts the data for one game and includes:

  • gameId
  • gameDuraton
  • blueWins
  • blueFirstBlood
  • blueFirstTower
  • blueFirstBaron
  • blueFirstDragon
  • blueFirstInhibitor
  • blueDragonKills
  • blueBaronKills
  • blueTowerKills
  • blueInhibitorKills
  • blueWardPlaced
  • blueWardkills
  • blueKills
  • blueDeath
  • blueAssist
  • blueChampionDamageDealt
  • blueTotalGold
  • blueTotalMinionKills
  • blueTotalLevel
  • blueAvgLevel
  • blueJungleMinionKills
  • blueKillingSpree
  • blueTotalHeal
  • blueObjectDamageDealt
  • redWins
  • redFirstBlood
  • redFirstTower
  • redFirstBaron
  • redFirstDragon
  • redFirstInhibitor
  • redDragonKills
  • redBaronKills
  • redTowerKills
  • redInhibitorKills
  • redWardPlaced
  • redWardkills
  • redKills
  • redDeath

  • redTotalLevel

Most games fall between the 20 and 30 minute mark. We know that the option to surrender only shows up at the 15 minute mark. Games that end before the 15 minute mark are an indication that a player was unable to load into the game or that a player left the game early, giving their teammates the option to end the game early.

Let's copy our dataframe and in our copy drop rows with games under 15 minutes, so we can later analyze games that were played out seperately from those that weren't.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

I discovered that red side wins only slightly more often, but gets the first dragon kill, first baron kill, and first inhibitor much more often than blue side. Blue side gets first blood and first tower more often than red side. There are also significantly fewer games the higher the rank, which is expected given the increased difficulty of the games with each rank.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I created a column that allowed me to see the game duration in minutes. I also created a copy of the dataframe and dropped rows with games less than 15 minutes. I did this because the option to forfeit doesn't appear until 15 minutes into the game, which means games that end before the 15 minute mark are indicative of a player who either was unable to connect or that left the game early. I believe it's important to analyze games in two categories, those who did not get played all the way through and those that did. Unfortunately, we don't have information for whether a game was forfeited or not, so I use 15 minutes as the distinguishing mark.

Interestingly, we can see that more games end only a few minutes in the higher ranked we get. This could very likely be due to the practice called "dodging". Dodging is leaving a game before it starts, when you believe you're going to lose. There is a period of time during the loading screen of the game where players can see the name of their oponents can use this time to look up the game history and stats of both their own teammates and the opposing team. Rather than "waste" 20+ minutes, some players prefer to simply dodge. The result is that the rest of the team will load into the game, but will be offered the chance to end early (at no penalty to them) since there is a missing person.

We can also see that games tend to be slightly shorter the higher ranked they are.

Wow! A lot of really interesting things here. The first thing I want to note is that first blood on both blue or red side, is NOT strongly correlated with anything. This is important, because (especially in high ranked games) many players get instantly upset and proclaim that the game is lost as soon as the opposite team gets the first kill (first blood). This practice of getting upset is called getting "tilted". Getting tilted can lead a player to get continually upset or annoyed, make rash decisions, and not play as well as they would have otherwise. This is as much a mental game as it is a skill based one.

The next thing I want to point out is that first tower is only weakly associated with winning for both red and blue sides. This is another common circumstance that is very likely to tilt a player. The incident of losing one of your team's towers first, especially before the 15 minute mark, has a super high likelihood of upsetting someone on the team to the point where they might just disconnect or stop trying, because they truly believe the game is over.

The variables most associated with winning for both blue and red sides are first inhibitor and tower kills. This would imply that if you want to win, your focus should be on the ultimate objective of destroying inhibitors and towers. This is not to say that secondary objectives such as securing dragon and possibly baron are not important, merely that they are natural occurrences if you've secured towers because you will be better positioned.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Red side typically places more wards and that leads me to believe this is the reason they win slightly more than blue side does. A reason for this is because players tend to favor/feel more comfortable on blue side and the worry about being behind or playing with a disadvantage could lead them to compensate by prioritizing vision.

Looking at champion damage dealt visualized the experience of slow and steady games vs snowballing. Snowballing is less common the higher the rank game is. It also further reinforced the notion that numbers from all variable fit smaller ranged the higher rank the games are.

First inhibitor and tower kills are the variable most indicative of a win for a team playing on either red or blue side.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

What was most surprising is that neither first blood nor first tower were strong indicators of a team winning the game. This is surprising because they are the two most common things to make players angry and lead to them ending the game early.

Conclusions¶

Vision (placing wards) is considerably important if a team wants to win. All members of the team must participate in order to reach higher levels of wards placed. Smaller mistakes/numbers matter more the higher ranked you are and your aim should be to allow yourself to scale in order to make steady progress and win over the course of the game. Regardless of rank, neither first blood nor first tower are indicative that the game is lost and players should work hard to maintain a balanced and positive mental outlook in the face of these experiences. The focus should instead be on pushing for the first inhibitor and the destruction of towers, as these are the highest indicators of a won game.
